snippet.textDisplay: I just don't like the "high functioning/ low functioning" labels. Or to say one has "mild" autism bcs it always depends almost on the approval of neurotypical societies and of mediocre psychiatrists. It's almost as if callous uninformed NT professionals want us to be like  "please let me be in your world" when it's everyone's world. Or to draw a scale on whose less or more different in a negative sense, or a pity case. It's simply that some autistics need more, less or different support or aids than others. A lot of people, including psychiatrists and psychologists sigh in relief and tell me how "lucky" I am for them considering me "high functioning", as if they knew my life and experiences for talking to me for 10 minutes. They can't fathom they saw me on a day where getting out of my apartment wasn't as terrifying, that I prepared thoroughly and that I'll be exhausted, that I won't be able get out for over a month, and that I might cry for hours once I'm back home just to heal from social interactions. Many mental health professionals even belief that we lack empathy, when that was never the case, it's the opposite, by now it's considered obsolete but some people are so mediocre that they don't care to help others in a job where they meet so many vulnerable people. We feel intense empathy and it can be overwhelming. Many also believe only white males can be autistic and that an autism diagnose it's out of the question for people who manage to look at people's eyes. They think it disappears with age, therefore absurdly believing that it can only present in male kids and teens. One big problem is that professionals aren't properly trained and that sadly the majority don't have the traits to be basically decent at their jobs, nor care to develop them (self-improvement, empathy, rigour, rationality, humbleness, observation, objectivity, selflessness, passion for the topic or topics they specialise in, an eye for details and patterns, bed side manner, selfresponsible; yes, a lot of autistic traits). Hence so many autistic adults, specially women, are undiagnosed or selfdiagnosed without getting the help we need when we are at our most vulnerable. Most medical professionals see children and teen diagnose as profitable too, so they don't care to diagnose adults.

snippet.textDisplay: Jubilee, please change the title of the video. Referring to people with ASD as “autistic people” diminishes who they are as people and reduces them to being solely characterized by ASD. As someone who has ASD and works with children who have ASD, we’re taught to refer to them as people first, and address their disability second. For example, “Do all people with autism think the same”. It’s the same as referring to other people as humans first, and not implying through our language that their disability or disorder defines or encompasses the whole of who they are. That’s why we don’t refer to others as “that Down syndrome girl” or “that cancer boy”. Language is a powerful factor in our perceptions of other people and a powerful factor in how we examine other’s views of us. Sorry to sound like such an SJW but I just want to make people aware.

snippet.textDisplay:
I like that they had someone there who is fully non-verbal. I think we are finally starting to see the spectrum of people with autism. I work with lower-functioning people with autism who are non-verbal. They understand quite a lot, but they are not able to care for themselves and struggle with daily tasks, can't read or write, and into their adulthood can't have a job, drive, or do adult-like activities, and their stimming behaviors are often extreme (loud noises and big movements).
I'd love to see some of these lower-functioning people on here, even if their parents/caretakers had to help speak for them. People with high functioning autism will speak about it and while they do make sure to often say it is only their experience, it makes it seem like their experience is more common. This is because people like those I work with can't speak up for themselves.

snippet.textDisplay:
In elementary school we had a boy who was non verbal autistic and our school had a "see life through his eyes" day where we had to do things like. Trying to do fine motor skills with thick gloves on, or try to listen to the teachers talk with the music blasting. Or read with goggles that had Vaseline over them.
It helped us all see why he would get over stimulated and scream and all of us helped him and loved him until we graduated. I'm lucky to have gone through a school system that helped us understand these things better

snippet.textDisplay:
Im autistic and I wanna answer these...
Do you find special offensive: Somewhat disagree. It can be used negatively but overall it's just a polite word for different.
Do you have trouble making friends: Agree. I just suck at making deep friendships. I'm 22 and have only made maybe 5 deep friendships my whole life.
Being diagnosed w autism helped me understand myself more: Strongly agree. One day you are just a freak, weirdo, outcast, different for no apparent reason and the next, you have a diagnosis, a name, a label, a reason for being the way you are, acting the way you are.
It bothers me when people pity me: Somewhat disagree. I'm not normal! I struggle! My struggles are obvious. Someone would be heartless to not feel bad for me.
I would rather not have autism: Agree. My life is significantly harder bc of my autism. I can't relate to people well. I can't function well. Ofc, without my autism I would be slightly different, but I'd be free and able to do so much more. Anyone who says no is lying or not autistic. Genuinely.
I feel connected to other ppl on the spectrum: Somewhat agree. Common issues unite us. Not much else to say.

snippet.textDisplay:
I’m autistic! These are my answers and thoughts for the questions.

One: Somewhat agree. Special needs is not bad but just ‘special’ is. Shaina was who I agreed with the most. Joe too!

Two: Agree. Making friends is hard unless you meet likeminded people. I’m much better at long term friendships and I really only have a couple friends. Jai was who I agreed the most with. But friends shouldn’t mind stimming.

Three: Strongly agree! It helped so much it’s insane! I was seen as crazy by people in school because of my meltdowns. There was initially some sadness about it because I wasn’t neurotypical. But now I’m much happier because I understand who I am.

Four: Somewhat disagree. It’s something I’ve gotten used to throughout my life despite not having a diagnosis until I was seventeen. I was 100% babied like Bella before and after my diagnosis. But I don’t resent being babied.

Five: Strongly disagree. Jai and Shaina sum it up perfectly. I wouldn’t be me and I live in a neurotypical work. I only want the world to understand me.

Six: Agree. Despite everyone being different, it’s something we have in common. I’m autistic and my s/o is autistic. We wouldn’t have the same relationship if one of us was NT. It helped us connect. Joe also sums it up.
